abstract: President Trump and Senator Elizabeth Warren, a Democrat harshly critical of Wall Street, may both favor separating retail and investment banking.
snippet: President Trump and Senator Elizabeth Warren, a Democrat harshly critical of Wall Street, may both favor separating retail and investment banking.
lead_paragraph: President Trump has vowed to roll back financial regulation, saying that it is preventing banks from lending and businesses from growing.

abstract: Closing New York’s main jail complex to put correctional facilities around the city is a tough sell politically. But it could be an improvement for criminal justice and no impediment to new condos.
snippet: Closing New York’s main jail complex to put correctional facilities around the city is a tough sell politically. But it could be an improvement for criminal justice and no impediment to new condos.
lead_paragraph: Of the 2.3 million people confined to correctional facilities in the United States, close to 650,000 are in local jails, rather than state or federal prisons, and less than a third have been convicted of anything. In theory, jail stays are intended to be short, but the excruciating pace of bureaucracy means that the accused, many of whom cannot afford bail, might end up behind bars for months or years before their cases reach resolution and they are sent, or not sent, to prison.

abstract: President Trump planned to sign an executive order targeting steel dumping, a measure aimed at China and a potential victory for his hard-line advisers.
snippet: President Trump planned to sign an executive order targeting steel dumping, a measure aimed at China and a potential victory for his hard-line advisers.
lead_paragraph: PALM BEACH, Fla. — The Trump administration is planning to roll out its first concrete measures against China on trade, administration officials said on Thursday, hardening its position toward America’s largest trading partner just as President Trump welcomed President Xi Jinping of China to his seaside club here for their first face-to-face meeting.

abstract: The New York Times has been examining problems at Rikers Island, as well as the New York City Correction Department, which oversees it. Here’s what you need to know.
snippet: The New York Times has been examining problems at Rikers Island, as well as the New York City Correction Department, which oversees it. Here’s what you need to know.
lead_paragraph: Mayor Bill de Blasio has declared that within the next decade, the jail complex at Rikers Island would be shut down. The mayor’s announcement was an acknowledgment that despite the hundreds of millions of dollars devoted to fixing the problems in recent years, the jail cannot be saved.

abstract: Jules Stewart’s new book emphasizes that “the city as we know it today came of age” in the years leading up to World War II.
snippet: Jules Stewart’s new book emphasizes that “the city as we know it today came of age” in the years leading up to World War II.
lead_paragraph: The title and cover photograph of Jules Stewart’s “Gotham Rising: New York in the 1930s” (I. B. Tauris, $29) is just what you would expect from a journalist and historian raised on comic book superheroes.

abstract: The family of David Rockefeller has brought flexibility, responsibility and a sense of gratitude to their philanthropy.
snippet: The family of David Rockefeller has brought flexibility, responsibility and a sense of gratitude to their philanthropy.
lead_paragraph: David Rockefeller, who died last week at 101, was a giant among American philanthropists. He continued the tradition of giving that ran from his grandfather, John D., the founder of Standard Oil; through his father, John Jr.; and his oldest brother, John III.
